<LEADPARA>  The ultimate English poetry anthology, containing every inspired or wretched
line published by 1,350 poets from early Anglo-Saxon times to 1900, will soon
be available on computer.;    "English Poetry," the entire output from 1,300
years, will be contained on four computer discs or one magnetic tape, 2,400
feet long, and available for $35,200.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BRITISH POETRY OF 1,300 YEARS COMPUTERIZED  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "It may sound expensive, but it will be cheaper than trying to acquire
nearly 5,000 volumes," said <PERSON>Stephen Pocock</PERSON>, the senior project editor at
publishers <ORGANIZATION>Chadwyck-Healey Ltd.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Cambridge</LOCATION>. The discs will become available
between <DATE>March 1992</DATE> and <DATE>March 1994.</DATE>;    "Some of these poets have not been
reprinted since their work was originally published in the 17th and 18th
centuries. The poetry will be indexed by author, title, part-title and key
words so that anyone searching it will be able to see if some poets borrowed
anything from their predecessors," <PERSON>Pocock</PERSON> said in an interview Friday.;    He
said the work stopped at <DATE>1900</DATE> because of copyright difficulties with 20th
century poetry.;    Publication is scheduled for three installments, one disc
each for the periods 600 to <DATE>1660</DATE> and <DATE>1661</DATE> to <DATE>1800</DATE> and the last two for the
<DATE>19th century</DATE>, which contains as much verse as the other two periods together,
<PERSON>Pocock</PERSON> said.;    "All the published work of these poets will be included, the
famous and the completely obscure, whether it was poetry of genius or just
plain awful. Even famous poets like (<LOCATION>William</LOCATION>) <PERSON>Wordsworth</PERSON> wrote some dire stuff
at times," he said.;    Even one of <PERSON>Wordsworth</PERSON>'s worst lines will be included:
"This piteous news so much it shocked her, She quite forgot to send the
doctor.";    Besides the great masters like <PERSON>William Shakespeare</PERSON>, <PERSON>John Milton</PERSON>
and <PERSON>Lord Byron</PERSON>, the project will include little-known versifiers.;    One is
<PERSON>William Tennant</PERSON>, whose epic 1822 poem "The Thane of Fife" has some memorable
imagery like, "Now, in the very navel of the sky" and "Morning's
golden-tassell'd shoes, Had leapt from sea and now in heaven walk dry.";   
"It's taken 15 people all <DATE>summer</DATE> just to count the words involved and there
are more than 1 billion characters," said <PERSON>John Russell</PERSON>, the publisher's sales
director.;    <PERSON>Pocock</PERSON> said the poets are those listed in "The New Cambridge
Bibliography of English Literature," issued by <ORGANIZATION>Cambridge University Press</ORGANIZATION> from
<DATE>1969</DATE> to <DATE>1972</DATE>, and which includes English translations of <ORGANIZATION>Welsh</ORGANIZATION>, Scottish and
Irish poets who wrote in other languages.;    "We expect university libraries
around the world, English faculties and some public libraries to buy it. Much
of the material is hard to come by and isn't available in some British
libraries," <PERSON>Pocock</PERSON> said.  </TEXT>
