<HEAD>Prefab Jail: Temporary Solution to Crowding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 graf after 9th pvs, `Jim Wordsworth,...' to add detail
on size of containers, use. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `Abell, a...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEESBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The red building tucked away in the scenic
mountains of <LOCATION>northwest Virginia</LOCATION> looks more like a schoolhouse than
the nation's first prefabricated jail made from converted shipping
containers.
   New picnic tables in the back overlook a lush green field.
There's plenty of room outside the building for exercise or
picnics. But the building is being noticed for more than its looks.
   ``I think what these people are doing for prison construction is
equivalent to what <PERSON>Henry Ford</PERSON> did for automobile construction,''
said <PERSON>Richard Abell</PERSON>, assistant <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> attorney general for justice
programs. ``<PERSON>Henry Ford</PERSON> did not invent the automobile, but he made
it accessible. What these people are doing is making prisons
accessible.''
   <PERSON>Abell</PERSON> said the <LOCATION>Loudoun County</LOCATION> facility is the first of its kind
in the country. He said what makes this jail different is ``no one
has ever taken these shipping containers already made, and made
them into jails.''
   Surfside 6 Industries of <ORGANIZATION>McLean</ORGANIZATION> built the six-cell, 23-cot jail
in 13 working days for <MONEY>$96,398</MONEY>. That translates into a cost of
about <MONEY>$4,000</MONEY> a bed.
   ``Ordinarily, it costs <MONEY>$40,000</MONEY> to <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> per bed space, and it
generally takes two years to build a jail or a prison,'' <PERSON>Abell</PERSON>
said. ``These guys put it together in two weeks. That's beyond
revolutionary.''
   <PERSON>Abell</PERSON> said another advantage is the flexibility of the prefab
jails.
   ``Like Tinkertoys, they can be rearranged if they need to be
changed in five or 10 years,'' <PERSON>Abell</PERSON> said. ``If the needs have
decreased, they're not stuck with it on the landscape. You don't
have a problem like <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> has with <LOCATION>Alcatraz</LOCATION> _ a big massive
sore on the landscape.''
   <PERSON>Jim Wordsworth</PERSON>, secretary and treasurer of <LOCATION>Surfside</LOCATION> 6, said the
prefab building could be used as a shelter for the homeless or to
store records.
   Each steel shipping container is 8 feet tall, 8 feet wide and 20
feet long, <PERSON>Wordsworth</PERSON> said. To convert it into a jail cell, the
container is insulated and a wall covering such as cement or
drywall is put on. The finished building uses traditional plumbing,
wiring and heating.
   <PERSON>Wordsworth</PERSON> said the used containers are transported to <ORGANIZATION>Surfside
6 Industries</ORGANIZATION>' factory in <LOCATION>Fort Lauderdale</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla.</LOCATION>, and put together
there, then shipped to the location. He said they can be built on
site too.
   Abell, a member of the <ORGANIZATION>National Institute of Corrections
Advisory Board</ORGANIZATION>, said prison crowding has become a national problem.
   ``Between <DATE>1963</DATE> and <DATE>1981</DATE>, our crime rate soared <PERCENT>337 percent</PERCENT> in
the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and prison construction in the same period went
up <PERCENT>27 percent</PERCENT>,'' <PERSON>Abell</PERSON> said.
   <LOCATION>Loudoun County</LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON>John Isom</PERSON> said there is a shortage of
about 3,000 beds in the <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>D.C.</LOCATION>, area, and of about 1,900
beds in northern <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>.
   He said the maximum-security prison in <LOCATION>Leesburg</LOCATION> has 63 beds and
averages 100 people a day. He said he plans to move at least 23
people who are in work-release programs to the prefab jail when it
opens this month.
   But <PERSON>Isom</PERSON> said, ``Overcrowding will continue unless someone
figures out a way to eradicate the drug problem.''
   Crowding causes many problems, he said, including violence.
   ``We have inmate fights a couple of times a week,'' <PERSON>Isom</PERSON> said.
   While counties elsewhere have agonized over finding sites and
money to build large, future-oriented buildings equipped with
computer-controlled security and even robot food carts, <PERSON>Isom</PERSON> said
he was looking for a quick and inexpensive solution.
   He and <PERSON>Wordsworth</PERSON> said the jail's security will be adequate.
<PERSON>Wordsworth</PERSON> said a special welding torch would be required to cut
through the walls, made of Insulcrete, a patented concrete with
high insulation quality.
   He said officials from all over the country are calling about
the jail.
   ``It's unbelievable,'' he said. ``They're bringing the county
administrator, the director of finance, the sheriff to look at this.
   ``It's unique, it's portable, you can set it down and then move
the whole structure,'' he said. ``There is so much citizen unrest
on the location of prisons and jails ... They can assure the
citizens they're temporarily solving a problem until they go
through all of the rituals of building.''
   <PERSON>Greg Bogdan</PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION>Federal Bureau of Prisons</ORGANIZATION>, said
the bureau isn't opposed to the prefab idea, but says it isn't the
long-term solution to the crowding problem.
   ``They're suitable for emergency situations, but they're not an
answer to the long-term prison problem as far as the bureau is
concerned,'' <PERSON>Bogdan</PERSON> said. ``There is still a need for permanent
facilities.''
</TEXT>
